{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":21409,"record_hash":"sha256:f4c303e99b9a21a895a53fde535c9627050a7559f619be53ef65cee1f22d2e51","timestamp":"2026-05-10T20:52:12.404Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"assistant","text":"I think we’re good for now. I would **not** add more GitMeta APIs yet.\n\nThe important thing we have now is the right primitive:\n\n```rust\nset_record(prefix, value)\nget_record::<T>(prefix)\n```\n\nThat gives us a clean way to round-trip scalar record-shaped metadata, which is exactly what the source metadata needs.\n\nThe other future reads are not painful enough yet to justify API surface:\n\n- session index: `get_value(\"gitbutler:agent-sessions\")`\n- source set: `get_value(\"<session>:sources\")`\n- transcript list: `list_entries(\"<session>:transcript\")`\n\nThose are still domain-specific enough that I’d rather let a future `but-agentlog` reader own the small glue instead of pushing helpers into GitMeta too early.\n\nThe one thing to keep in mind: `get_record` is best for **clean scalar prefixes**, like:\n\n```text\ngitbutler:agent-session:<session-key>:source:<source-key>:*\n```\n\nIt is not ideal for the mixed session prefix itself, because that prefix contains strings, sets, and lists:\n\n```text\n:schema\n:updated-at\n:sources\n:transcript\n```\n\nThat is okay. A future agentlog reader can read session-level values explicitly and use `get_record` for source metadata.\n\nSo my recommendation is:\n\n- no more GitMeta API changes right now\n- no agentlog reader until there is an actual consumer\n- when we do build a reader, keep it in `but-agentlog` and hide all raw key spelling there\n\nThat keeps us positioned without getting ahead of ourselves.","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-10T20:52:12.404Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"assistant","phase":"final_answer"}}}